On 5/30/07, Nic James Ferrier &lt;nferrier@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &quot;Alan Dean&quot; &lt;alan.dean@...&gt; writes:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; In any event, I believe that resource-space decomposition is
&gt; &gt; fundamentally hard.
&gt;
&gt; it&#39;s not trivial. I wouldn&#39;t say it was hard exactly.

Perhaps I should elaborate further.

1. Take a typical &#39;jobbing developer&#39; supporting a typical e-commerce platform.

2. Ask him/her to decompose the resource-space of the application.

3. Watch the carnage.

I don&#39;t mean to demean &#39;jobbing developers&#39; at all - these are the
people who keep all our favourite shopping sites up and running. My
point is that their focus is *not* on resource abstractions - it is on
user functionality (often small scale), middle-tier and back-end
maintenance and extension (often against spaghetti code and within
highly diffuse boundaries) using databases whose schemas are often
ancient.

For the typical reader of this list, who I expect is personally
motivated by this problem domain and is likely well-read, I am sure
that resource-space decomposition is a walk in the park ;-) but if
REST is to fulfil it&#39;s promise then I personally believe that we need
to win the hearts and minds of those &#39;jobbing developers&#39;.

Alan
